{[show S]Roman Key Card Blackwood keeps a partnership out of bad slams as well as into good ones. When the response shows a keycard missing, the asker must have the discipline to stop.
[BID 1N] You open 1NT, fifteen to seventeen balanced. Your partner bids 2\C, Stayman, asking for a four-card major.
[BID 2H] You show four hearts with 2\H. Your partner jumps to 3\S, a slam try agreeing hearts.
[BID 4N] You bid 4NT, Roman Key Card Blackwood for hearts. Your partner answers 5\H, showing two keycards without the trump queen, which leaves one of the five keycards off the partnership, so slam is out and the bidding stops in 5\H.
[BID Pass] You pass; 5\H is the final contract.
[show NS]The keycard ask uncovered a missing ace, so 5H is the limit; pressing on would be a slam off a cashing ace. The discipline to stop is the point, since a keycard ask must be ready to hear a bad answer. 5H makes exactly eleven.}
